			<div class="row align-center">
				<div class="medium-12 column text-center">
					<a href=""><h1 class="title">Ideas for a better <strong>Digital Scrapbook</strong></h1></a>
					<span class="date"><a href="">February 4th, 2015</a> - from <a href="">Notetaking Apps</a></span>
				</div>
			</div>
			<div class="row align-center">
				<article class="medium-8 small-10 column text-left">

					
					<p>The key to this note taking app is seamless workflow.</p>

					<h2 id="awesomebarextended">AwesomeBar extended</h2>

					<p>The Firefox AwesomeBar is pretty self explanatory. When I had a stint using Google Chrome, the URL bar always bothered
						me as it favored search results and <em>exact</em> URLs from my History over the URL that I wanted to go to. <code>trello</code> would be auto completed to something like <code>https://trello.com/b/zttawhOT/</code> instead of <code>https://trello.com</code>.
						It wasn&#8217;t fun for me. With that in mind, fiddling with the default behavior of the AwesomeBar is dangerous.</p>

					<h2 id="keywords">Keywords</h2>

					<p>My first thought would be to require a keyword to initiate the <a href="http://notational.net/">Notational Velocity</a>				style search/new note interface. It solves the issue of separating web requests like <code>trello</code> from note requests
						like <code>ideas for band names</code>. As easy as the keyword solution would be to implement, it feels lackluster. It
						fails my dream of a seamless gateway between the web and the mind.</p>

					<h2 id="themostobvious">The Most Obvious</h2>

					<p>And then it hit me. Duh, this&#8217;ll just work right at the start! The AwesomeBar&#8217;s engineers, in deciding what
						a user might use the bar for included <em>bookmark support</em>! If you start to search for <code>trello</code>, you&#8217;ll
						be confronted with any bookmarks you have that partially match the string <code>trello</code>! The AwesomeBar handles what
						results to display first, but the result is visible as a bookmark!</p>

					<figure>
						<img src="http://i.imgur.com/IFxNZ9R.png" alt="Firefoxs AwesomeBar can utilize the tags, title, and URL when searching through bookmarks."
						/>
						<figcaption>Firefox&#8217;s AwesomeBar can utilize the tags, title, and URL when searching through bookmarks.</figcaption>
					</figure>



					<p>The next step is to implement new note creation. The keyword solution remains the easiest to handle indifference Notational
						Velocity has towards search and note creation. There are several solutions to handle this creation.</p>

					<ul>
						<li>Searches that don&#8217;t exactly match a note show a link to create new note

							<ul>
								<li>Extra action to create note</li>
							</ul>
						</li>
						<li>Press a modifier <code>shift+enter</code> to create a new note with the title from the URL bar

							<ul>
								<li>Separates notes from the URL and could slow down the user creating a note as they have to memorize a shortcut.</li>
								<li>Not a bad solution, but not <em>instantly</em> understandable.</li>
							</ul>
						</li>
					</ul>

					<p>This will require more thought. </p>
				</article>
