		<div class="blogpost">
			<div class="row align-center text-center">
				<div class="column">
					<a href=""><h1 class="title">A way to make <strong>bookmarks useful</strong></h1></a>
					<span class="date"><a href="">January 26th, 2015</a> - from <a href="">Notetaking Apps</a></span>
				</div>
			</div>
			<div class="row align-center">
				<article class="medium-8 small-10 column">
					

					<p>I&#8217;ve don&#8217;t have a good how I&#8217;ll actually make this, but here goes.</p>

					<h2 id="bookmarksasdata">Bookmarks as Data</h2>

					<p>Firefox Bookmarks have a URL, a hierarchy, and a <em>notes</em> section. I can&#8217;t imagine that anyone actually uses
						the notes section, but what if someone did? What if, you stuck an <strong>entire note taking app inside of a bookmark</strong>.
						Just simple Markdown to format, with a specialized URL to handle viewing the bookmark as a note.</p>

					<h2 id="itsbeendone">It&#8217;s been done</h2>

					<p><a href="http://topaddon.com/index.html">QuickFox</a> is, to be frank, a pretty lame app. It looks like it was pulled
						out of the 2005 Windows XP school of application design with the content taking the full width of the screen and relying
						on a window hovering above your Firefox tabs. Even if you try to load the addon as a tab, the addon relies on its own
						internal tabs. But even with that said, it&#8217;s a <em>truly brilliant idea</em>. Your notes are stored as bookmarks,
						thereby making sync a simple and unobtrusive experience as your browser handles it in the background through whatever
						service you want.</p>

					<p>I just want to take that one step further and turn it into full blown bookmark/scrapbooking system along the lines of
						Evernote.</p>

					<h2 id="themailboxappofnote-taking">The Mailbox App of Note-taking</h2>

					<p>Note-taking isn&#8217;t that glamorous. For the longest time I&#8217;ve relied on Evernote to handle formatting and sync
						and it works pretty well. It provides more metadata than I could ask for with support for authors, tags, even location.
						What it doesn&#8217;t do is offer a simple service. In fact, it&#8217;s a fucking mess.</p>

					<p>If you &#8216;clip&#8217; a website into Evernote, you&#8217;re stuck with the silly formatting and bastardized data structure
						that the site used. My gripe isn&#8217;t with the algorithms they&#8217;re using to harvest the content, but the presentation
						of the content. <em>Personally</em>, when I take notes, I want my result to be clean and to-the-point. Basically, I want
						some nice clean Markdown I can turn into HTML if it needs to be styled. I don&#8217;t want minute control over the fonts,
						the line-height, the colors for each individual note. I want one style and appropriate formatting.</p>

					<h2 id="browsersandnotationalvelocity">Browsers and Notational Velocity</h2>

					<p><a href="http://notational.net/">Notational Velocity is</a> is brilliant. <a href="http://brettterpstra.com/projects/nvalt/">nvALT</a>				is, so far, my favorite brand of it with awesome Markdown support, custom font display support, and Simplenote. The key
						to Notational Velocity is its reliance on the search bar, much like <em>a certain</em> other piece of critical software,
						the browser URL bar.</p>

					<h4 id="whatifthebrowserurlbarcouldnotonlybethegatewaytothewebbutthegatewaytoyourmemories.">What if the browser URL bar could not only be the gateway to the web, but the gateway to your memories.</h4>

					<p>Pretty lofty, right? Every startup needs a tagline like that. So imagine your reading list merged with your notes. A certain
						workflow that encourages documentation of thoughts.</p>


				</article>
